# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bacterial-genetics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] It is a mechanism of horizontal gene transfer as are transformation and transduction although these two other mechanisms do not involve cell-to-cell contact.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] Classical *E. coli* bacterial conjugation is often regarded as the bacterial equivalent of sexual reproduction or mating, since it involves the exchange of genetic material.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] However, it is not sexual reproduction, since no exchange of gamete occurs, and indeed no generation of a new organism: instead, an existing organism is transformed.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] During classical *E. coli* conjugation, the *donor* cell provides a conjugative or mobilizable genetic element that is most often a plasmid or transposon.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] Most conjugative plasmids have systems ensuring that the *recipient* cell does not already contain a similar element.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] The genetic information transferred is often beneficial to the recipient.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] Benefits may include antibiotic resistance, xenobiotic tolerance or the ability to use new metabolites.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] Other elements can be detrimental, and may be viewed as bacterial parasites.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] Conjugation in *Escherichia coli* by spontaneous zygogenesis and in *Mycobacterium smegmatis* by distributive conjugal transfer differ from the better studied classical *E. coli* conjugation in that these cases involve substantial blending of the parental genomes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] The process was discovered by Joshua Lederberg and Edward Tatum in 1946.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] Pilus attaches to recipient cell and brings the two cells together.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] The mobile plasmid is nicked and a single strand of DNA is then transferred to the recipient cell.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] Both cells synthesize a complementary strand to produce a double stranded circular plasmid and also reproduce pili; both cells are now viable donors for the conjugative plasmid.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] The F-factor is an episome (a plasmid that can integrate itself into the bacterial chromosome by homologous recombination) with a length of about 100 kb.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] It is a classical example of a conjugative plasmid.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] It carries its own origin of replication, the *oriV*, and an origin of transfer, or *oriT*.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] There can only be one copy of the F-plasmid in a given bacterium, either free or integrated, and bacteria that possess a copy are called *F-positive* or *F-plus* (denoted F+).
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] Cells that lack F plasmids are called *F-negative* or *F-minus* (F−) and as such can function as recipient cells.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] Among other genetic information, the F-plasmid carries a *tra* and *trb* locus, which together are about 33 kb long and consist of about 40 genes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] The *tra* locus includes the *pilin* gene and regulatory genes, which together form pili on the cell surface.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] The locus also includes the genes for the proteins that attach themselves to the surface of F− bacteria and initiate conjugation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] Though there is some debate on the exact mechanism of conjugation it seems that the pili are the structures through which DNA exchange occurs.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] The F-pili are extremely resistant to mechanical and thermochemical stress, which guarantees successful conjugation in a variety of environments.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] Several proteins coded for in the *tra* or *trb* locus seem to open a channel between the bacteria and it is thought that the TraD enzyme, located at the base of the pilus, initiates membrane fusion.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] When conjugation is initiated by a signal, the **relaxase** enzyme creates a nick in one of the strands of the conjugative plasmid at the *oriT*.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] Relaxase may work alone, or in a complex of over a dozen proteins known collectively as a **relaxosome**.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] In the F-plasmid system, the relaxase enzyme is called TraI and the relaxosome consists of TraI, TraY, TraM and the integrated host factor IHF.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] The nicked strand, or *T-strand*, is then unwound from the unbroken strand and transferred to the recipient cell in a 5'-terminus to 3'-terminus direction.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] The strand is thought to be transferred through the pilus into the recipient cell.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] The remaining strand is replicated either independent of conjugative action (vegetative replication beginning at the *oriV*) or in concert with conjugation (conjugative replication similar to the rolling circle replication of lambda phage).
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] Conjugative replication may require a second nick before successful transfer can occur.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] A recent report claims to have inhibited conjugation with chemicals that mimic an intermediate step of this second nicking event.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] If the F-plasmid that is transferred has previously been integrated into the donor's genome (producing an Hfr strain ["High Frequency of Recombination"]) some of the donor's chromosomal DNA may also be transferred with the plasmid DNA.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] The amount of chromosomal DNA that is transferred depends on how long the two conjugating bacteria remain in contact.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] In common laboratory strains of *E. coli* the transfer of the entire bacterial chromosome takes about 100 minutes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] The transferred DNA can then be integrated into the recipient genome via homologous recombination.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] A cell culture that contains in its population cells with non-integrated F-plasmids usually also contains a few cells that have integrated their plasmids.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] It is these cells that are responsible for the low-frequency chromosomal gene transfers that occur in such cultures.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] Some strains of bacteria with an integrated F-plasmid can be isolated and grown in pure culture.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] Because such strains transfer chromosomal genes very efficiently they are called **Hfr** (**h**igh **f**requency of **r**ecombination).
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] The *E. coli* genome was originally mapped by interrupted mating experiments in which various Hfr cells in the process of conjugation were sheared from recipients after less than 100 minutes (initially using a Waring blender).
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] The genes that were transferred were then investigated.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] In addition to classical bacterial conjugation described above for *E. coli*, a form of conjugation referred to as spontaneous zygogenesis (Z-mating for short) is observed in certain strains of *E. coli*.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] In Z-mating there is complete genetic mixing, and unstable diploids are formed that throw off phenotypically haploid cells, of which some show a parental phenotype and some are true recombinants.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] Conjugation in *Mycobacteria smegmatis*, like conjugation in *E. coli*, requires stable and extended contact between a donor and a recipient strain, is DNase resistant, and the transferred DNA is incorporated into the recipient chromosome by homologous recombination.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] However, unlike *E. coli* Hfr conjugation, mycobacterial conjugation is chromosome rather than plasmid based.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] Furthermore, in contrast to *E. coli* Hfr conjugation, in *M. smegmatis* all regions of the chromosome are transferred with comparable efficiencies.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] The lengths of the donor segments vary widely, but have an average length of 44.2kb.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] Since a mean of 13 tracts are transferred, the average total of transferred DNA per genome is 575kb.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] This process is referred to as "Distributive conjugal transfer." Gray et al. found substantial blending of the parental genomes as a result of conjugation and regarded this blending as reminiscent of that seen in the meiotic products of sexual reproduction.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] Hyperthermophilic archaea encode pili structurally similar to the bacterial conjugative pili.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] It has been suggested that in these archaea the conjugation machinery has been fully domesticated for promoting DNA repair through homologous recombination rather than spread of mobile genetic elements.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] In addition to the VirB2-like conjugative pilus, the Ced and Ted systems include components for the VirB6-like transmembrane mating pore and the VirB4-like ATPase.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] Bacteria related to the nitrogen fixing *Rhizobia* are an interesting case of inter-kingdom conjugation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] For example, the tumor-inducing (Ti) plasmid of *Agrobacterium* and the root-tumor inducing (Ri) plasmid of *A. rhizogenes* contain genes that are capable of transferring to plant cells.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] The expression of these genes effectively transforms the plant cells into opine-producing factories.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] Opines are used by the bacteria as sources of nitrogen and energy.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] Infected cells form crown gall or root tumors.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] The Ti and Ri plasmids are thus endosymbionts of the bacteria, which are in turn endosymbionts (or parasites) of the infected plant.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] The Ti and Ri plasmids can also be transferred between bacteria using a system (the *tra*, or transfer, operon) that is different and independent of the system used for inter-kingdom transfer (the *vir*, or virulence, operon).
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] Such transfers create virulent strains from previously avirulent strains.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] Conjugation is a convenient means for transferring genetic material to a variety of targets.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] In laboratories, successful transfers have been reported from bacteria to yeast, plants, mammalian cells, diatoms and isolated mammalian mitochondria.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] Conjugation has advantages over other forms of genetic transfer including minimal disruption of the target's cellular envelope and the ability to transfer relatively large genetic materials (see the above discussion of *E. coli* chromosome transfer).
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] In plant engineering, *Agrobacterium*-like conjugation complements other standard vehicles such as tobacco mosaic virus (TMV).
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] While TMV is capable of infecting many plant families these are primarily herbaceous dicots.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-conjugation] *Agrobacterium*-like conjugation is also primarily used for dicots, but monocot recipients are not uncommon.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-genetics] Like other organisms, bacteria also breed true and maintain their characteristics from generation to generation, yet at the same time, exhibit variations in particular properties in a small proportion of their progeny.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-genetics] Though heritability and variations in bacteria had been noticed from the early days of bacteriology, it was not realised then that bacteria too obey the laws of genetics.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-genetics] Even the existence of a bacterial nucleus was a subject of controversy.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-genetics] The differences in morphology and other properties were attributed by Nageli in 1877, to bacterial pleomorphism, which postulated the existence of a single, a few species of bacteria, which possessed a protein capacity for a variation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-genetics] With the development and application of precise methods of pure culture, it became apparent that different types of bacteria retained constant form and function through successive generations.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-genetics] This led to the concept of monomorphism.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-genetics] Transformation in bacteria was first observed in 1928 by Frederick Griffith and later (in 1944) examined at the molecular level by Oswald Avery and his colleagues who used the process to demonstrate that DNA was the genetic material of bacteria.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-genetics] In transformation, a cell takes up extraneous DNA found in the environment and incorporates it into its genome (genetic material) through recombination.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-genetics] Not all bacteria are competent to be transformed, and not all extracellular DNA is competent to transform.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-genetics] To be competent to transform, the extracellular DNA must be double-stranded and relatively large.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-genetics] To be competent to be transformed, a cell must have the surface protein **Competent Factor'**, which binds to the extracellular DNA in an energy requiring reaction.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-genetics] However bacteria that are not naturally competent can be treated in such a way to make them competent, usually by treatment with calcium chloride, which make them more permeable.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-genetics] Bacterial conjugation is the transfer of genetic material (plasmid) between bacterial cells by direct cell-to-cell contact or by a bridge-like connection between two cells.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-genetics] Discovered in 1946 by Joshua Lederberg and Edward Tatum, conjugation is a mechanism of horizontal gene transfer as are transformation and transduction although these two other mechanisms do not involve cell-to-cell contact.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-genetics] Bacterial conjugation is often regarded as the bacterial equivalent of sexual reproduction or mating since it involves the exchange of genetic material.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-genetics] During conjugation the donor cell provides a conjugative or mobilizable genetic element that is most often a plasmid or transposon.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-genetics] Most conjugative plasmids have systems ensuring that the recipient cell does not already contain a similar element.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-genetics] Such beneficial plasmids may be considered bacterial endosymbionts.
[src:bacterial-genetics/bacterial-genetics] Other elements, however, may be viewed as bacterial parasites and conjugation as a mechanism evolved by them to allow for their spread.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Horizontal gene transfer is the primary mechanism for the spread of antibiotic resistance in bacteria, and plays an important role in the evolution of bacteria that can degrade novel compounds such as human-created pesticides and in the evolution, maintenance, and transmission of virulence.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] It often involves temperate bacteriophages and plasmids.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Genes responsible for antibiotic resistance in one species of bacteria can be transferred to another species of bacteria through various mechanisms of HGT such as transformation, transduction and conjugation, subsequently arming the antibiotic resistant genes' recipient against antibiotics.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] The rapid spread of antibiotic resistance genes in this manner is becoming a challenge to manage in the field of medicine.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Ecological factors may also play a role in the HGT of antibiotic resistant genes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Horizontal gene transfer is recognized as a pervasive evolutionary process that distributes genes between divergent prokaryotic lineages and can also involve eukaryotes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] HGT events are thought to occur less frequently in eukaryotes than in prokaryotes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] However, growing evidence indicates that HGT is relatively common among many eukaryotic species and can have an impact on adaptation to novel environments.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Its study, however, is hindered by the complexity of eukaryotic genomes and the abundance of repeat-rich regions, which complicate the accurate identification and characterization of transferred genes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] It is postulated that HGT promotes the maintenance of a universal life biochemistry and, subsequently, the universality of the genetic code.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Griffith's experiment, reported in 1928 by Frederick Griffith, was the first experiment suggesting that bacteria are capable of transferring genetic information through a process known as transformation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Griffith's findings were followed by research in the late 1930s and early 1940s that isolated DNA as the material that communicated this genetic information.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Inter-bacterial gene transfer was first described in Japan in a 1959 publication that demonstrated the transfer of antibiotic resistance between different species of bacteria.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] In the mid-1980s, Syvanen postulated that biologically significant lateral gene transfer has existed since the beginning of life on Earth and has been involved in shaping all of evolutionary history.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] As Jian, Rivera and Lake (1999) put it: "Increasingly, studies of genes and genomes are indicating that considerable horizontal transfer has occurred between prokaryotes" (see also Lake and Rivera, 2007).
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] The phenomenon appears to have had some significance for unicellular eukaryotes as well.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Grafting of one plant to another can transfer chloroplasts (organelles in plant cells that conduct photosynthesis), mitochondrial DNA, and the entire cell nucleus containing the genome to potentially make a new species.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Some Lepidoptera (e.g. monarch butterflies and silkworms) have been genetically modified by horizontal gene transfer from the wasp bracovirus.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Bites from insects in the family Reduviidae (assassin bugs) can, via a parasite, infect humans with the trypanosomal Chagas disease, which can insert its DNA into the human genome.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] It has been suggested that lateral gene transfer to humans from bacteria may play a role in cancer.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Palmer state: "Horizontal gene transfer (HGT) has played a major role in bacterial evolution and is fairly common in certain unicellular eukaryotes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Due to the increasing amount of evidence suggesting the importance of these phenomena for evolution (see below) molecular biologists such as Peter Gogarten have described horizontal gene transfer as "A New Paradigm for Biology".
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] A transposable element (TE) (also called a transposon or jumping gene) is a mobile segment of DNA that can sometimes pick up a resistance gene and insert it into a plasmid or chromosome, thereby inducing horizontal gene transfer of antibiotic resistance.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Horizontal transposon transfer (HTT) refers to the passage of pieces of DNA that are characterized by their ability to move from one locus to another between genomes by means other than parent-to-offspring inheritance.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Horizontal gene transfer has long been thought to be crucial to prokaryotic evolution, but there is a growing amount of data showing that HTT is a common and widespread phenomenon in eukaryote evolution as well.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] On the transposable element side, spreading between genomes via horizontal transfer may be viewed as a strategy to escape purging due to purifying selection, mutational decay and/or host defense mechanisms.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Non-autonomous elements may be less likely to transfer horizontally compared to autonomous elements because they do not encode the proteins required for their own mobilization.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] The structure of these non-autonomous elements generally consists of an intronless gene encoding a transposase protein, and may or may not have a promoter sequence.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Those that do not have promoter sequences encoded within the mobile region rely on adjacent host promoters for expression.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Horizontal transfer is thought to play an important role in the TE life cycle.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] In plants, it appears that LTR retrotransposons of the Copia superfamilies, especially those with low copy numbers from the Ale and Ivana lineages, are more likely to undergo horizontal transfer between different plant species.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] HTT has been shown to occur between species and across continents in both plants and animals (Ivancevic et al.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] 2013), though some TEs have been shown to more successfully colonize the genomes of certain species over others.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Both spatial and taxonomic proximity of species has been proposed to favor HTTs in plants and animals.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] It is unknown how the density of a population may affect the rate of HTT events within a population, but close proximity due to parasitism and cross contamination due to crowding have been proposed to favor HTT in both plants and animals.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] In plants, the interaction between lianas and trees has been shown to facilitate HTT in natural ecosystems.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Successful transfer of a transposable element requires delivery of DNA from donor to host cell (and to the germ line for multi-cellular organisms), followed by integration into the recipient host genome.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Though the actual mechanism for the transportation of TEs from donor cells to host cells is unknown, it is established that naked DNA and RNA can circulate in bodily fluid.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Many proposed vectors include arthropods, viruses, freshwater snails (Ivancevic et al.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] 2013), endosymbiotic bacteria, and intracellular parasitic bacteria.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] In some cases, even TEs facilitate transport for other TEs.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] The arrival of a new TE in a host genome can have detrimental consequences because TE mobility may induce mutation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] However, HTT can also be beneficial by introducing new genetic material into a genome and promoting the shuffling of genes and TE domains among hosts, which can be co-opted by the host genome to perform new functions.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Moreover, transposition activity increases the TE copy number and generates chromosomal rearrangement hotspots.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] HTT detection is a difficult task because it is an ongoing phenomenon that is constantly changing in frequency of occurrence and composition of TEs inside host genomes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Furthermore, few species have been analyzed for HTT, making it difficult to establish patterns of HTT events between species.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] These issues can lead to the underestimation or overestimation of HTT events between ancestral and current eukaryotic species.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Horizontal gene transfer is typically inferred using bioinformatics methods, either by identifying atypical sequence signatures ("parametric" methods) or by identifying strong discrepancies between the evolutionary history of particular sequences compared to that of their hosts.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] The transferred gene (xenolog) found in the receiving species is more closely related to the genes of the donor species than would be expected.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] One demonstrated method to find HGT events is through Shotgun Metagenomics; breaking down then sequencing DNA in a sample by its contiguous regions and looking for phylogenetic mismatches, which can be inferred as instances of Horizontal Gene Transfer.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] The virus called *Mimivirus* infects amoebae.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Another virus, called *Sputnik*, also infects amoebae, but it cannot reproduce unless mimivirus has already infected the same cell.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Horizontal gene transfer is common among bacteria, even among very distantly related ones, and also between bacteria and archaea.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] This process is thought to be a significant cause of increased drug resistance when one bacterial cell acquires resistance, and the resistance genes are transferred to the other species.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Transposition and horizontal gene transfer, along with strong natural selective forces have led to multi-drug resistant strains of *S. aureus* and many other pathogenic bacteria.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Horizontal gene transfer also plays a role in the spread of virulence factors, such as exotoxins and exoenzymes, amongst bacteria.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] A prime example concerning the spread of exotoxins is the adaptive evolution of Shiga toxins in *E. coli* through horizontal gene transfer via transduction with *Shigella* species of bacteria.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Strategies to combat certain bacterial infections by targeting these specific virulence factors and mobile genetic elements have been proposed.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] For example, horizontally transferred genetic elements play important roles in the virulence of *E. coli*, *Salmonella*, *Streptococcus* and *Clostridium perfringens*.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] In prokaryotes, restriction-modification systems are known to provide immunity against horizontal gene transfer and in stabilizing mobile genetic elements.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Genes encoding restriction modification systems have been reported to move between prokaryotic genomes within mobile genetic elements (MGE) such as plasmids, prophages, insertion sequences/transposons, integrative conjugative elements (ICE), and integrons.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Still, they are more frequently a chromosomal-encoded barrier to MGE than an MGE-encoded tool for cell infection.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Lateral gene transfer via a mobile genetic element, namely the integrated conjugative element (ICE) *Bs1* has been reported for its role in the global DNA damage SOS response of the gram positive *Bacillus subtilis*.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Furthermore, it has been linked with the radiation and desiccation resistance of *Bacillus pumilus* SAFR-032 spores, isolated from spacecraft cleanroom facilities.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Transposon insertion elements have been reported to increase the fitness of gram-negative *E. coli* strains through either major transpositions or genome rearrangements, and increasing mutation rates.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] In a study on the effects of long-term exposure of simulated microgravity on non-pathogenic *E. coli*, the results showed transposon insertions occur at loci, linked to SOS stress response.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Both of these studies have implications for microbial growth, adaptation to and antibiotic resistance in real time space conditions.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Horizontal gene transfer is particularly active in bacterial genomes around the production of secondary or specialized metabolites.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Certain areas of genes known as hotspots further increase the likelihood of horizontally transferred secondary metabolite-producing genes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] The promiscuity of enzymes is a reoccurring theme in this particular theatre.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Natural transformation is a bacterial adaptation for DNA transfer (HGT) that depends on the expression of numerous bacterial genes whose products are responsible for this process.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] In general, transformation is a complex, energy-requiring developmental process.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] In order for a bacterium to bind, take up and recombine exogenous DNA into its chromosome, it must become competent, that is, enter a special physiological state.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Competence development in *Bacillus subtilis* requires expression of about 40 genes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] The DNA integrated into the host chromosome is usually (but with infrequent exceptions) derived from another bacterium of the same species, and is thus homologous to the resident chromosome.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] The capacity for natural transformation occurs in at least 67 prokaryotic species.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Competence for transformation is typically induced by high cell density and/or nutritional limitation, conditions associated with the stationary phase of bacterial growth.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Competence appears to be an adaptation for DNA repair.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Transformation in bacteria can be viewed as a primitive sexual process, since it involves interaction of homologous DNA from two individuals to form recombinant DNA that is passed on to succeeding generations.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Although transduction is the form of HGT most commonly associated with bacteriophages, certain phages may also be able to promote transformation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] As mentioned before, conjugation is a method of horizontal gene transfer through cell to cell contact.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Through the process of conjugation, type IV Secretion Systems (T4SS) are used to passage on DNA from the donor cell to the recipient cell.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] These T4SS encoded within the plasmid carry other proteins and genes that help supplement the cell in conjugation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Research has shown that there are Single Binding DNA Binding proteins (SSBs) also encoded within the conjugative plasmid may help with conjugation and cell viability.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] This is thought to be the case because SSBs naturally are expressed to help with stabilizing single-stranded DNA (ssDNA).
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] SSBs will also recruit other proteins like RadD or RecA expressed in events of DNA recombination, repair, and replication.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Further showcasing their possible role in conjugation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Although it may help, studies have also shown for proteins like SSB to not be essential in conjugation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] For example, the plasmid pCF10 from *Enterococcus faecalis*, a gram-positive bacterium, has a SSB like-protein called PrgE and was classified for not being required for conjugation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] More work needs to be done on why proteins that bind to ssDNA are encoded into conjugative plasmids.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Conjugation in the case of microbiomes and symbioses is very important.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] From this process new genes are acquired that lead to increasing genetic diversity and evolution such as the acquisition of antibiotic resistance genes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] *Mycobacterium tuberculosis* is a species that has evolved through methods like conjugation while gaining antibiotic resistance.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] This evolution or increase in genetic diversity is also seen in many other species.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Due to this, there is a huge concern on how impactful conjugation or horizontal gene transfer can be on human health and your microbiome as pathogenic microbes can become more pathogenic.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Studies have shown that even our own microbiome has a plethora of antimicrobial genes which if transferred to pathogenic microbes could be detrimental.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Conjugation in *Mycobacterium smegmatis*, like conjugation in *E. coli*, requires stable and extended contact between a donor and a recipient strain, is DNase resistant, and the transferred DNA is incorporated into the recipient chromosome by homologous recombination.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] However, unlike *E. coli* high frequency of recombination conjugation (Hfr), mycobacterial conjugation is a type of HGT that is chromosome rather than plasmid based.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Furthermore, in contrast to *E. coli* (Hfr) conjugation, in *M. smegmatis* all regions of the chromosome are transferred with comparable efficiencies.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Substantial blending of the parental genomes was found as a result of conjugation, and this blending was regarded as reminiscent of that seen in the meiotic products of sexual reproduction.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Haloarchaea are aerobic halophiles thought to have evolved from anaerobic methanogens.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] A large amount of their genome, 126 composite gene families, are derived from genetic material from bacterial genomes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] This has allowed them to adapt to extremely salty environments.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] The archaeon *Sulfolobus solfataricus*, when UV irradiated, strongly induces the formation of type IV pili which then facilitates cellular aggregation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Exposure to chemical agents that cause DNA damage also induces cellular aggregation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Other physical stressors, such as temperature shift or pH, do not induce aggregation, suggesting that DNA damage is a specific inducer of cellular aggregation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] UV-induced cellular aggregation mediates intercellular chromosomal HGT marker exchange with high frequency, and UV-induced cultures display recombination rates that exceed those of uninduced cultures by as much as three orders of magnitude.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] *S. solfataricus* cells aggregate preferentially with other cells of their own species.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Frols et al. and Ajon et al. suggested that UV-inducible DNA transfer is likely an important mechanism for providing increased repair of damaged DNA via homologous recombination.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] This process can be regarded as a simple form of sexual interaction.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Another thermophilic species, *Sulfolobus acidocaldarius*, is able to undergo HGT.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] *S. acidocaldarius* can exchange and recombine chromosomal markers at temperatures up to 84 °C.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] UV exposure induces pili formation and cellular aggregation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Cells with the ability to aggregate have greater survival than mutants lacking pili that are unable to aggregate.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] The frequency of recombination is increased by DNA damage induced by UV-irradiation and by DNA damaging chemicals.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] The *ups* operon, containing five genes, is highly induced by UV irradiation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] The proteins encoded by the *ups* operon are employed in UV-induced pili assembly and cellular aggregation leading to intercellular DNA exchange and homologous recombination.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Since this system increases the fitness of *S. acidocaldarius* cells after UV exposure, Wolferen et al. considered that transfer of DNA likely takes place in order to repair UV-induced DNA damages by homologous recombination.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] "Sequence comparisons suggest recent horizontal transfer of many genes among diverse species including across the boundaries of phylogenetic 'domains'.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Through research into the growing issue of antibiotic resistance certain compounds have been observed to promote horizontal gene transfer.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] The transfer of antibiotic resistance genes (ARGs) through conjugation is significantly accelerated when donor cells with plasmids and recipient cells are introduced to each other in the presence of one of the pharmaceuticals.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] These findings are from 2021 and due to the widespread use of non-antibiotic pharmaceuticals, more research needs to be done in order to further understanding on the issue.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Alongside non-antibiotic pharmaceuticals, other compounds relevant to antibiotic resistance have been tested such as malachite green, ethylbenzene, styrene, 2,4-dichloroaniline, trioxymethylene, o-xylene solutions, p-nitrophenol (PNP), p-aminophenol (PAP), and phenol (PhOH).
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] It is a global concern that ARGs have been found in wastewater treatment plants Textile wastewater has been found to contain 3- to 13-fold higher abundance of mobile genetic elements than other samples of wastewater.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] The cause of this is the organic compounds used for textile dying (*o*-xylene, ethylbenzene, trioxymethylene, styrene, 2,4-dichloroaniline, and malachite green) raising the frequency of conjugative transfer when bacteria and plasmid (with donor) are introduced in the presence of these molecules.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] When textile wastewater combines with wastewater from domestic sewage, the ARGs present in wastewater are transferred at a higher rate due to the addition of textile dyeing compounds increasing the occurrence of HGT.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Other organic pollutants commonly found in wastewater have been the subject of similar experiments.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] A 2021 study used similar methods of using plasmid in a donor and mixing that with a receptor in the presence of compound in order to test horizontal gene transfer of antibiotic resistance genes but this time in the presence of phenolic compounds.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Phenolic compounds are commonly found in wastewater and have been found to change functions and structures of the microbial communities during the wastewater treatment process.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Additionally, HGT increases in frequency in the presence of the compounds p-nitrophenol (PNP), p-aminophenol (PAP), and phenol.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] These compounds result in a 2- to 9-fold increase in HGT (p-nitrophenol being on the lower side of 2-fold increases and p-aminophenol and phenol having a maximum increase of 9-fold).
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] This increase in HGT is on average less than the compounds ibuprofen, naproxen, gemfibrozil, diclofenac, propranolol, o-xylene, ethylbenzene, trioxymethylene, styrene, 2,4-dichloroaniline, and malachite green but their increases is still significant.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] The study that came to this conclusion is similar to the study on horizontal gene transfer and non-antibiotic pharmaceuticals in that it was done in 2021 and leaves room for more research, specifically in the focus of the study which is activated sludge.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Heavy metals have also been found to promote conjugative transfer of antibiotic resistance genes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] The paper that led to the discovery of this was done in 2017 during the emerging field of horizontal gene transfer assisting compound research.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Metals assist in the spread of antibiotic resistance through both co-resistance as well as cross-resistance mechanisms.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] In quantities relevant to the environment, Cu(II), Ag(I), Cr(VI), and Zn(II) promote HGT from donor and receptor strains of E. coli.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] The presence of these metals triggered SOS response from bacterial cells and made the cells more permeable.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] These are the mechanisms that make even low levels of heavy metal pollution in the environment impact HGT and therefore the spread of ARGs.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Promiscuous DNA is a form of horizontal gene transfer that transmits genetic information across organellar barriers.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Promiscuous DNA transfer has substantial evidence in its movement across the genome of numerous organisms, from movements in chloroplast to the nucleus, chloroplast to the mitochondria, and mitochondria to the nucleus.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] John Ellis defined this type of transpositional transfer mutation as "intracellular promiscuity".
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Ellis further explored the phenomenon of "intracellular promiscuity" through the experiments of David Stern and David Lonsdale, in which genetic transfer between chloroplasts to mitochondria was discovered, aiding in the definition and discovery of promiscuous DNA.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] While much remains to be understood about how promiscuous DNA undergoes movement and transfer, numerous experiments have pointed to plastid sequences, ptDNA, as a key player.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Plasmids, with their mobile nature and crucial role in horizontal gene transfer, are seen as a significant element in DNA that exchanges genetic information.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] This mobility makes ptDNA a potential donor for promiscuous DNA to traverse organellar barriers.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] NUMTs (nuclear sequences of mitochondrial) are a type of promiscuous DNA that arises from the natural transfer of mitochondria DNA (mtDNA) to the nuclear genome (nDNA).
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] These NUMTs, with their varying frequencies, sizes, and features, contribute to the genetic diversity across all eukaryotes and, in some cases, to diseases among humans.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] NUPTs (nuclear plastid DNA sequences) are a type of promiscuous DNA that arises from the natural transfer of ptDNA (plastid DNA) into nDNA.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] These fragments of ptDNA, similar to NUMTs in frequency, size, and features, also exhibit variability across species.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Genetic engineering is essentially horizontal gene transfer, albeit with synthetic expression cassettes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] The Sleeping Beauty transposon system (SB) was developed as a synthetic gene transfer agent that was based on the known abilities of Tc1/mariner transposons to invade genomes of extremely diverse species.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] The SB system has been used to introduce genetic sequences into a wide variety of animal genomes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Horizontal gene transfer is a potential confounding factor in inferring phylogenetic trees based on the sequence of one gene.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] For example, given two distantly related bacteria that have exchanged a gene a phylogenetic tree including those species will show them to be closely related because that gene is the same even though most other genes are dissimilar.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] For this reason, it is often ideal to use other information to infer robust phylogenies such as the presence or absence of genes or, more commonly, to include as wide a range of genes for phylogenetic analysis as possible.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] For example, the most common gene to be used for constructing phylogenetic relationships in prokaryotes is the 16S ribosomal RNA gene since its sequences tend to be conserved among members with close phylogenetic distances, but variable enough that differences can be measured.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] However, in recent years it has also been argued that 16s rRNA genes can also be horizontally transferred.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Although this may be infrequent, the validity of 16s rRNA-constructed phylogenetic trees must be reevaluated.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] There exist several methods to infer such phylogenetic networks.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Using single genes as phylogenetic markers, it is difficult to trace organismal phylogeny in the presence of horizontal gene transfer.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Combining the simple coalescence model of cladogenesis with rare HGT horizontal gene transfer events suggest there was no single most recent common ancestor that contained all of the genes ancestral to those shared among the three domains of life.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Each contemporary molecule has its own history and traces back to an individual molecule cenancestor.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Horizontal gene transfer poses a possible challenge to the concept of the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) at the root of the tree of life that was first formulated by Carl Woese, which led him to propose the Archaea as a third domain of life.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Scientists are broadly agreed on symbiogenesis, that mitochondria in eukaryotes derived from alpha-proteobacterial cells and that chloroplasts came from ingested cyanobacteria, and other gene transfers may have affected early eukaryotes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] However, a LUCA can be identified, so horizontal transfers must have been relatively limited.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Other early HGTs are thought to have happened.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] The first common ancestor (FUCA), earliest ancestor of LUCA, had other descendants that had their own lineages.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] These now-extinct sister lineages of LUCA descending from FUCA are thought to have horizontally transferred some of their genes into the genome of early descendants of LUCA.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] It has been remarked that, despite the complications, the detection of horizontal gene transfers brings valuable phylogenetic and dating information.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] The potential of HGT to be used for dating phylogenies has recently been confirmed.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] The acquisition of new genes has the potential to disorganize the other genetic elements and hinder the function of the bacterial cell, thus affecting the competitiveness of bacteria.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Consequently, bacterial adaptation lies in a conflict between the advantages of acquiring beneficial genes, and the need to maintain the organization of the rest of its genome.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Horizontally transferred genes are typically concentrated in only ~1% of the chromosome (in regions called hotspots).
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] This concentration increases with genome size and with the rate of transfer.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Hotspots diversify by rapid gene turnover; their chromosomal distribution depends on local contexts (neighboring core genes), and content in mobile genetic elements.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Hotspots concentrate most changes in gene repertoires, reduce the trade-off between genome diversification and organization, and should be treasure troves of strain-specific adaptive genes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Most mobile genetic elements and antibiotic resistance genes are in hotspots, but many hotspots lack recognizable mobile genetic elements and exhibit frequent homologous recombination at flanking core genes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/horizontal-gene-transfer] Overrepresentation of hotspots with fewer mobile genetic elements in naturally transformable bacteria suggests that homologous recombination and horizontal gene transfer are tightly linked in genome evolution.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] A **plasmid** is a small, extrachromosomal DNA molecule within a cell that is physically separated from chromosomal DNA and can replicate independently.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] They are most commonly found as small circular, double-stranded DNA molecules in bacteria and archaea; however plasmids are sometimes present in eukaryotic organisms as well.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Plasmids often carry useful genes, such as those involved in antibiotic resistance, virulence, secondary metabolism and bioremediation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] While chromosomes are large and contain all the essential genetic information for living under normal conditions, plasmids are usually very small and contain additional genes for special circumstances.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Artificial plasmids are widely used as vectors in molecular cloning, serving to drive the replication of recombinant DNA sequences within host organisms.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] In the laboratory, plasmids may be introduced into a cell via transformation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Synthetic plasmids are available for procurement over the internet by various vendors using submitted sequences typically designed with software, if a design does not work the vendor may make additional edits from the submission.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Plasmids are considered *replicons*, units of DNA capable of replicating autonomously within a suitable host.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] However, plasmids, like viruses, are not generally classified as life.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Plasmids are transmitted from one bacterium to another (even of another species) mostly through conjugation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] This host-to-host transfer of genetic material is one mechanism of horizontal gene transfer, and plasmids are considered part of the mobilome.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Plasmids vary in size from 1 to over 400 kbp, and the number of identical plasmids in a single cell can range from one up to thousands.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] In order for plasmids to replicate independently within a cell, they must possess a stretch of DNA that can act as an origin of replication.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] The self-replicating unit, in this case, the plasmid, is called a replicon.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] A typical bacterial replicon may consist of a number of elements, such as the gene for plasmid-specific replication initiation protein (Rep), repeating units called iterons, DnaA boxes, and an adjacent AT-rich region.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Smaller plasmids make use of the host replicative enzymes to make copies of themselves, while larger plasmids may carry genes specific for the replication of those plasmids.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] A few types of plasmids can also insert into the host chromosome, and these integrative plasmids are sometimes referred to as episomes in prokaryotes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Plasmids almost always carry at least one gene.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Many of the genes carried by a plasmid are beneficial for the host cells, for example: enabling the host cell to survive in an environment that would otherwise be lethal or restrictive for growth.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Plasmids can also provide bacteria with the ability to fix nitrogen.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Some plasmids, called cryptic plasmids, don't appear to provide any clear advantage to its host, yet still persist in bacterial populations.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] However, recent studies show that they may play a role in antibiotic resistance by contributing to heteroresistance within bacterial populations.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Naturally occurring plasmids vary greatly in their physical properties.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Their size can range from very small mini-plasmids of less than 1-kilobase pairs (kbp) to very large megaplasmids of several megabase pairs (Mbp).
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] At the upper end, little differs between a megaplasmid and a minichromosome.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Plasmids are generally circular, but examples of linear plasmids are also known.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] These linear plasmids require specialized mechanisms to replicate their ends.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Plasmids may be present in an individual cell in varying number, ranging from one to several hundreds.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] The normal number of copies of plasmid that may be found in a single cell is called the plasmid copy number, and is determined by how the replication initiation is regulated and the size of the molecule.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Larger plasmids tend to have lower copy numbers.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Low-copy-number plasmids that exist only as one or a few copies in each bacterium are, upon cell division, in danger of being lost in one of the segregating bacteria.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Such single-copy plasmids have systems that attempt to actively distribute a copy to both daughter cells.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] These systems, which include the parABS system and parMRC system, are often referred to as the partition system or partition function of a plasmid.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Plasmids of *linear* form are unknown among phytopathogens with one exception, *Rhodococcus fascians*.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Plasmids may be classified in a number of ways.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Plasmids can be broadly classified into conjugative plasmids and non-conjugative plasmids.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Conjugative plasmids contain a set of transfer genes which promote sexual conjugation between different cells.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] In the complex process of conjugation, plasmids may be transferred from one bacterium to another via sex pili encoded by some of the transfer genes (see figure).
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Non-conjugative plasmids are incapable of initiating conjugation, hence they can be transferred only with the assistance of conjugative plasmids.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] An intermediate class of plasmids are mobilizable, and carry only a subset of the genes required for transfer.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] They can parasitize a conjugative plasmid, transferring at high frequency only in its presence.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Plasmids can also be classified into incompatibility groups.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] A microbe can harbour different types of plasmids, but different plasmids can only exist in a single bacterial cell if they are compatible.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] If two plasmids are not compatible, one or the other will be rapidly lost from the cell.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Different plasmids may therefore be assigned to different incompatibility groups depending on whether they can coexist together.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Incompatible plasmids (belonging to the same incompatibility group) normally share the same replication or partition mechanisms and can thus not be kept together in a single cell.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Incompatibility typing (or Inc typing) was traditionally achieved by genetic phenotyping methods, testing whether cells stably transmit plasmid pairs to their progeny.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] This has largely been superseded by genetic methods such as PCR, and more recently by whole-genome sequencing methods with bioinformatic tools such as PlasmidFinder.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Another way to classify plasmids is by function.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Plasmids can belong to more than one of these functional groups.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] With the wider availability of whole genome sequencing which is able to capture the genetic sequence of plasmids, methods have been developed to cluster or type plasmids based on their sequence content.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Plasmid multi-locus sequence typing (pMLST) is based on chromosomal Multilocus sequence typing by matching the sequence of replication machinery genes to databases of previously classified sequences.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] If the sequence allele matches the database, this is used as the plasmid classification, and therefore has higher sensitivity than a simple presence or absence test of these genes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] A related method is to use average nucleotide identity between plasmids to find close genetic neighbours.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Tools which use this approach include COPLA and MOB-cluster.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Creating typing classifications using unsupervised learning, that is without a pre-existing database or 'reference-free', has been shown to be useful in grouping plasmids in new datasets without biasing or being limited to representations in a pre-built database—tools to do this include mge-cluster.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] As plasmid frequently change their gene content and order, modelling genetic distances between them using methods designed for point mutations can lead to poor estimates of the true evolutionary distance between plasmids.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Tools such as pling find homologous sequence regions between plasmids, and more accurately reconstruct the number of evolutionary events (structural variants) between each pair, then use unsupervised clustering approaches to group plasmids.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Although most plasmids are double-stranded DNA molecules, some consist of single-stranded DNA, or predominantly double-stranded RNA.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] RNA plasmids are non-infectious extrachromosomal linear RNA replicons, both encapsidated and unencapsidated, which have been found in fungi and various plants, from algae to land plants.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] In many cases, however, it may be difficult or impossible to clearly distinguish RNA plasmids from RNA viruses and other infectious RNAs.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Chromids are elements that exist at the boundary between a chromosome and a plasmid, found in about 10% of bacterial species sequenced by 2009.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] These elements carry core genes and have codon usage similar to the chromosome, yet use a plasmid-type replication mechanism such as the low copy number RepABC.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] As a result, they have been variously classified as minichromosomes or megaplasmids in the past.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] In *Vibrio*, the bacterium synchronizes the replication of the chromosome and chromid by a conserved genome size ratio.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Artificially constructed plasmids may be used as vectors in genetic engineering.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] These plasmids serve as important tools in genetics and biotechnology labs, where they are commonly used to clone and amplify (make many copies of) or express particular genes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] A wide variety of plasmids are commercially available for such uses.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] The gene to be replicated is normally inserted into a plasmid that typically contains a number of features for their use.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] These include a gene that confers resistance to particular antibiotics (ampicillin is most frequently used for bacterial strains), an origin of replication to allow the bacterial cells to replicate the plasmid DNA, and a suitable site for cloning (referred to as a multiple cloning site).
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] DNA structural instability can be defined as a series of spontaneous events that culminate in an unforeseen rearrangement, loss, or gain of genetic material.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Such events are frequently triggered by the transposition of mobile elements or by the presence of unstable elements such as non-canonical (non-B) structures.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Accessory regions pertaining to the bacterial backbone may engage in a wide range of structural instability phenomena.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Well-known catalysts of genetic instability include direct, inverted, and tandem repeats, which are known to be conspicuous in a large number of commercially available cloning and expression vectors.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Insertion sequences can also severely impact plasmid function and yield, by leading to deletions and rearrangements, activation, down-regulation or inactivation of neighboring gene expression.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Therefore, the reduction or complete elimination of extraneous noncoding backbone sequences would pointedly reduce the propensity for such events to take place, and consequently, the overall recombinogenic potential of the plasmid.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Plasmids are the most-commonly used bacterial cloning vectors.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] These cloning vectors contain a site that allows DNA fragments to be inserted, for example a multiple cloning site or polylinker which has several commonly used restriction sites to which DNA fragments may be ligated.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] After the gene of interest is inserted, the plasmids are introduced into bacteria by a process called transformation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] These plasmids contain a selectable marker, usually an antibiotic resistance gene, which confers on the bacteria an ability to survive and proliferate in a selective growth medium containing the particular antibiotics.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] The cells after transformation are exposed to the selective media, and only cells containing the plasmid may survive.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] In this way, the antibiotics act as a filter to select only the bacteria containing the plasmid DNA.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] The vector may also contain other marker genes or reporter genes to facilitate selection of plasmids with cloned inserts.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Bacteria containing the plasmid can then be grown in large amounts, harvested, and the plasmid of interest may then be isolated using various methods of plasmid preparation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] A plasmid cloning vector is typically used to clone DNA fragments of up to 15 kbp.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] To clone longer lengths of DNA, lambda phage with lysogeny genes deleted, cosmids, bacterial artificial chromosomes, or yeast artificial chromosomes are used.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Suicide vectors are plasmids that are unable to replicate in the host cell and therefore have to integrate in the chromosome or disappear.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] One example of these vectors are pMQ30 plasmid.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] This plasmid has SacB gene from *Bacillus subtilis* which can be induced by sucrose and will be lethal when expressed in Gram-negative bacteria.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] The benefit of this system( two-step success monitoring ) shows when the experiment design needs a target gene to be integrated into the chromosome of the bacterial host.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] In the first step after transforming the host cells with the plasmid, a media with specific antibiotic could be used to select for bacteria that contain the plasmid.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] The second step makes sure that only the bacteria with integrated plasmid would survive.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Since the plasmid contain the SacB gene that will induce toxicity in presence of sucrose, only the bacteria would survive and grow that has the plasmid integrated in their chromosome.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Another major use of plasmids is to make large amounts of proteins.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] In this case, researchers grow bacteria containing a plasmid harboring the gene of interest.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Just as the bacterium produces proteins to confer its antibiotic resistance, it can also be induced to produce large amounts of proteins from the inserted gene.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] This is a cheap and easy way of mass-producing the protein, for example, utilizing the rapid reproduction of E.coli with a plasmid containing the insulin gene leads to a large production of insulin.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Plasmids may also be used for gene transfer as a potential treatment in gene therapy so that it may express the protein that is lacking in the cells.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Some forms of gene therapy require the insertion of therapeutic genes at pre-selected chromosomal target sites within the human genome.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Plasmid vectors are one of many approaches that could be used for this purpose.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Zinc finger nucleases (ZFNs) offer a way to cause a site-specific double-strand break to the DNA genome and cause homologous recombination.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Plasmids encoding ZFN could help deliver a therapeutic gene to a specific site so that cell damage, cancer-causing mutations, or an immune response is avoided.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Plasmids were historically used to genetically engineer the embryonic stem cells of rats to create rat genetic disease models.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] The limited efficiency of plasmid-based techniques precluded their use in the creation of more accurate human cell models.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] However, developments in adeno-associated virus recombination techniques, and zinc finger nucleases, have enabled the creation of a new generation of isogenic human disease models.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Plasmids assist in transporting biosynthetic gene clusters - a set of gene that contain all the necessary enzymes that lead to the production of special metabolites (formally known as secondary metabolite).
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] A benefit of using plasmids to transfer BGC is demonstrated by using a suitable host that can mass produce specialized metabolites, some of these molecules are able to control microbial population.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Plasmids can contain and express several BGCs with a few plasmids known to be exclusive for transferring BGCs.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] BGC's can also be transfers to the host organism's chromosome, utilizing a plasmid vector, which allows for studies in gene knockout experiments.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] By using plasmids for the uptake of BGCs, microorganisms can gain an advantage as production is not limited to antibiotic resistant biosynthesis genes but the production of toxins/antitoxins.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] The term *episome* was introduced by François Jacob and Élie Wollman in 1958 to refer to extra-chromosomal genetic material that may replicate autonomously or become integrated into the chromosome.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Since the term was introduced, however, its use has changed, as *plasmid* has become the preferred term for autonomously replicating extrachromosomal DNA.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] At a 1968 symposium in London some participants suggested that the term *episome* be abandoned, although others continued to use the term with a shift in meaning.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Today, some authors use *episome* in the context of prokaryotes to refer to a plasmid that is capable of integrating into the chromosome.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] The integrative plasmids may be replicated and stably maintained in a cell through multiple generations, but at some stage, they will exist as an independent plasmid molecule.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] In the context of eukaryotes, the term *episome* is used to mean a non-integrated extrachromosomal closed circular DNA molecule that may be replicated in the nucleus.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Viruses are the most common examples of this, such as herpesviruses, adenoviruses, and polyomaviruses, but some are plasmids.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Other examples include aberrant chromosomal fragments, such as double minute chromosomes, that can arise during artificial gene amplifications or in pathologic processes (e.g., cancer cell transformation).
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Episomes in eukaryotes behave similarly to plasmids in prokaryotes in that the DNA is stably maintained and replicated with the host cell.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Cytoplasmic viral episomes (as in poxvirus infections) can also occur.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Some episomes, such as herpesviruses, replicate in a rolling circle mechanism, similar to bacteriophages (bacterial phage viruses).
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Others replicate through a bidirectional replication mechanism (*Theta type* plasmids).
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] In either case, episomes remain physically separate from host cell chromosomes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Several cancer viruses, including Epstein-Barr virus and Kaposi's sarcoma-associated herpesvirus, are maintained as latent, chromosomally distinct episomes in cancer cells, where the viruses express oncogenes that promote cancer cell proliferation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] In cancers, these episomes passively replicate together with host chromosomes when the cell divides.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] When these viral episomes initiate lytic replication to generate multiple virus particles, they generally activate cellular innate immunity defense mechanisms that kill the host cell.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Some plasmids or microbial hosts include an addiction system or postsegregational killing system (PSK), such as the hok/sok (host killing/suppressor of killing) system of plasmid R1 in *Escherichia coli*.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] This variant produces both a long-lived poison and a short-lived antidote.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Several types of plasmid addiction systems (toxin/ antitoxin, metabolism-based, ORT systems) were described in the literature and used in biotechnical (fermentation) or biomedical (vaccine therapy) applications.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Daughter cells that retain a copy of the plasmid survive, while a daughter cell that fails to inherit the plasmid dies or suffers a reduced growth-rate because of the lingering poison from the parent cell.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Finally, the overall productivity could be enhanced.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] In contrast, plasmids used in biotechnology, such as pUC18, pBR322 and derived vectors, hardly ever contain toxin-antitoxin addiction systems, and therefore need to be kept under antibiotic pressure to avoid plasmid loss.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Plasmids replicated and expressed by the eukaryotic cell's machinery may reside in the cytoplasm or the cell nucleus, with different plasmids having different preferences.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] In addition, eukaryotes have two endosymbiotic organelles with their own genome and genetic machinery – the mitochondrion and the chloroplast – and each of these can carry plasmids in addition to the main organellar genome molecule.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] The natural linear pGKL plasmids from *Kluyveromyces lactis* are responsible for killer phenotypes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] They can be put into the common baker's yeast *S. cerevisiae*.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Plasmids enter the nucleus during cell division, being rolled up in the nuclear envelope as it is reformed.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] As a result, nuclear plasmids do not work in non-dividing cells.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] The natural 2 micron plasmid (named after the fact that it is about 2 μm in size) is found in the common baker's yeast *S. cerevisiae*.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] It resides in the nucleus in 30–40 copies per cell.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] It is often modified for genetic engineering of yeast.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Artificial plasmids are put into mammalian cells to make them produce a certain gene product.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] They are also used to identify and quantitatively study regulatory elements, with the assumption that these elements on a plasmid would act similarly to a copy on the chromosome.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Being DNA sequences in the nucleus, the plasmid molecule also interactes with histone proteins.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] The mitochondria of many higher plants contain self-replicating, extra-chromosomal linear or circular DNA molecules which have been considered to be plasmids.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] These can range from 0.7 kb to 20 kb in size.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] The plasmids have been generally classified into two categories- circular and linear.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Circular plasmids have been isolated and found in many different plants, with those in *Vicia faba and Chenopodium album* being the most studied and whose mechanism of replication is known.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] The circular plasmids can replicate using the θ model of replication (as in *Vicia faba*) and through rolling circle replication (as in *C.album*).
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Linear plasmids have been identified in some plant species such as *Beta vulgaris*, *Brassica napus, Zea mays*, etc. but are rarer than their circular counterparts.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] The function and origin of these plasmids remains largely unknown.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] It has been suggested that the circular plasmids share a common ancestor, some genes in the mitochondrial plasmid have counterparts in the nuclear DNA suggesting inter-compartment exchange.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Plasmids are often used to purify a specific sequence, since they can easily be purified away from the rest of the genome.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] For their use as vectors, and for molecular cloning, plasmids often need to be isolated.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] There are several methods to isolate plasmid DNA from bacteria, ranging from the plasmid extraction kits (miniprep to the maxiprep or bulkprep), alkaline lysis, enzymatic lysis, and mechanical lysis .
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] The former can be used to quickly find out whether the plasmid is correct in any of several bacterial clones.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] The yield is a small amount of impure plasmid DNA, which is sufficient for analysis by restriction digest and for some cloning techniques.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] In the latter, much larger volumes of bacterial suspension are grown from which a maxi-prep can be performed.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] In essence, this is a scaled-up miniprep followed by additional purification.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] This results in relatively large amounts (several hundred micrograms) of very pure plasmid DNA.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Many commercial kits have been created to perform plasmid extraction at various scales, purity, and levels of automation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Plasmid DNA may appear in one of five conformations, which (for a given size) run at different speeds in a gel during electrophoresis.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] The rate of migration for small linear fragments is directly proportional to the voltage applied at low voltages.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] At higher voltages, larger fragments migrate at continuously increasing yet different rates.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Thus, the resolution of a gel decreases with increased voltage.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] At a specified, low voltage, the migration rate of small linear DNA fragments is a function of their length.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Large linear fragments (over 20 kb or so) migrate at a certain fixed rate regardless of length.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] This is because the molecules 'respirate', with the bulk of the molecule following the leading end through the gel matrix.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Restriction digests are frequently used to analyse purified plasmids.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] These enzymes specifically break the DNA at certain short sequences.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] The resulting linear fragments form 'bands' after gel electrophoresis.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] It is possible to purify certain fragments by cutting the bands out of the gel and dissolving the gel to release the DNA fragments.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Because of its tight conformation, supercoiled DNA migrates faster through a gel than linear or open-circular DNA.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] The use of plasmids as a technique in molecular biology is supported by bioinformatics software.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] These programs record the DNA sequence of plasmid vectors, help to predict cut sites of restriction enzymes, and to plan manipulations.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Examples of software packages that handle plasmid maps are ApE, Clone Manager, GeneConstructionKit, Geneious, Genome Compiler, LabGenius, Lasergene, MacVector, pDraw32, Serial Cloner, UGENE, VectorFriends, Vector NTI, and WebDSV.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] These pieces of software help conduct entire experiments in silico before doing wet experiments.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Many plasmids have been created over the years and researchers have given out plasmids to plasmid databases such as the non-profit organisations Addgene and BCCM/GeneCorner.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] One can find and request plasmids from those databases for research.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Researchers also often upload plasmid sequences to the NCBI database, from which sequences of specific plasmids can be retrieved.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] There have been multiple efforts to create curated and quality controlled databases from these uploaded sequences; an early example is by Orlek *et al*, which limited itself to *Enterobacteriaceae* plasmids, while COMPASS also encompassed plasmids from other bacteria.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] More recently, PLSDB was made as a more up to date curated database of NCBI plasmids, and as of 2024 contains over 72,000 entries.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] A similar database is pATLAS, which additionally includes visual analytics tools to show relationships between plasmids.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] The largest plasmid database made from publicly available data is IMG/PR, which not only contains full plasmid sequences retrieved from NCBI, but novel plasmid genomes found from metagenomes and metatranscriptomes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] Other datasets have been created by sequencing and computing plasmid genomes from pre-existing bacterial collections, e.g. the NORM collection and the Murray Collection.
[src:bacterial-genetics/plasmid] In addition to academic and non-profit repositories, plasmid DNA is also produced at industrial scale by specialized biotechnology companies supporting gene therapy and biopharmaceutical development, including Aldevron, Cobra Biologics and 3PBIOVIAN.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] Transduction was discovered in *Salmonella* by Norton Zinder and Joshua Lederberg at the University of Wisconsin–Madison in 1952.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] Transduction happens through either the lytic cycle or the lysogenic cycle.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] When bacteriophages (viruses that infect bacteria) that are lytic infect bacterial cells, they harness the replicational, transcriptional, and translation machinery of the host bacterial cell to make new viral particles (virions).
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] The new phage particles are then released by lysis of the host.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] In the lysogenic cycle, the phage chromosome is integrated as a prophage into the bacterial chromosome, where it can stay dormant for extended periods of time.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] If the prophage is induced (by UV light for example), the phage genome is excised from the bacterial chromosome and initiates the lytic cycle, which culminates in lysis of the cell and the release of phage particles.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] Generalized transduction (see below) occurs in both cycles during the lytic stage, while specialized transduction (see below) occurs when a prophage is excised in the lysogenic cycle.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] The packaging of bacteriophage DNA into phage capsids has low fidelity.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] Small pieces of bacterial DNA may be packaged into the bacteriophage particles.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] There are two ways that this can lead to transduction.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] Generalized transduction occurs when random pieces of bacterial DNA are packaged into a phage.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] It happens when a phage is in the lytic stage, at the moment that the viral DNA is packaged into phage heads.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] If the virus replicates using 'headful packaging', it attempts to fill the head with genetic material.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] If the viral genome results in spare capacity, viral packaging mechanisms may incorporate bacterial genetic material into the new virion.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] Alternatively, generalized transduction may occur via recombination.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] Generalized transduction is a rare event and occurs on the order of 1 phage in 11,000.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] The new virus capsule that contains part bacterial DNA then infects another bacterial cell.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] If the DNA was originally a plasmid, it will re-circularize inside the new cell and become a plasmid again.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] If the new DNA matches with a homologous region of the recipient cell's chromosome, it will exchange DNA material similar to the actions in bacterial recombination.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] An example of specialized transduction is λ phage in *Escherichia coli*.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] Transduction with viral vectors can be used to insert or modify genes in mammalian cells.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] It is often used as a tool in basic research and is actively researched as a potential means for gene therapy.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] In these cases, a plasmid is constructed in which the genes to be transferred are flanked by viral sequences that are used by viral proteins to recognize and package the viral genome into viral particles.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] This plasmid is inserted (usually by transfection) into a producer cell together with other plasmids (DNA constructs) that carry the viral genes required for the formation of infectious virions.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] In these producer cells, the viral proteins expressed by these packaging constructs bind the sequences on the DNA/RNA (depending on the type of viral vector) to be transferred and insert it into viral particles.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] For safety, none of the plasmids used contains all the sequences required for virus formation, so that simultaneous transfection of multiple plasmids is required to get infectious virions.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] Moreover, only the plasmid carrying the sequences to be transferred contains signals that allow the genetic materials to be packaged in virions so that none of the genes encoding viral proteins are packaged.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] Viruses collected from these cells are then applied to the cells to be altered.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] The initial stages of these infections mimic infection with natural viruses and lead to expression of the genes transferred and (in the case of lentivirus/retrovirus vectors) insertion of the DNA to be transferred into the cellular genome.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] However, since the transferred genetic material does not encode any of the viral genes, these infections do not generate new viruses (the viruses are "replication-deficient").
[src:bacterial-genetics/transduction-genetics] Some enhancers have been used to improve transduction efficiency such as polybrene, protamine sulfate, retronectin, and DEAE Dextran.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] In molecular biology and genetics, **transformation** is the genetic alteration of a bacterial cell resulting from the direct uptake and incorporation of exogenous genetic material from its surroundings through the cell membrane(s).
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] For transformation to take place, the recipient bacterium must be in a state of competence, which might occur in nature as a time-limited response to environmental conditions such as starvation and cell density, and may also be induced in a laboratory.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] In transformation, the genetic material passes through the intervening medium, and uptake is completely dependent on the recipient bacterium.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] As of 2014 about 80 species of bacteria were known to be capable of transformation, about evenly divided between Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria; the number might be an overestimate since several of the reports are supported by single papers.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Transformation in bacteria was first demonstrated in 1928 by the British bacteriologist Frederick Griffith.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Griffith was interested in determining whether injections of heat-killed bacteria could be used to vaccinate mice against pneumonia.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] However, he discovered that a non-virulent strain of *Streptococcus pneumoniae* could be made virulent after being exposed to heat-killed virulent strains.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Griffith hypothesized that some "transforming principle" from the heat-killed strain was responsible for making the harmless strain virulent.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] In 1944 this "transforming principle" was identified as being genetic by Oswald Avery, Colin MacLeod, and Maclyn McCarty.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] They isolated DNA from a virulent strain of *S. pneumoniae* and using just this DNA were able to make a harmless strain virulent.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] It was originally thought that *Escherichia coli*, a commonly used laboratory organism, was refractory to transformation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] However, in 1970, Morton Mandel and Akiko Higa showed that *E. coli* may be induced to take up DNA from bacteriophage λ without the use of helper phage after treatment with calcium chloride solution.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Two years later in 1972, Stanley Norman Cohen, Annie Chang and Leslie Hsu showed that CaCl 2 treatment is also effective for transformation of plasmid DNA.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] The method of transformation by Mandel and Higa was later improved upon by Douglas Hanahan.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] The discovery of artificially induced competence in *E. coli* created an efficient and convenient procedure for transforming bacteria which allows for simpler molecular cloning methods in biotechnology and research, and it is now a routinely used laboratory procedure.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Transformation using electroporation was developed in the late 1980s, increasing the efficiency of in-vitro transformation and increasing the number of bacterial strains that could be transformed.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Transformation of animal and plant cells was also investigated with the first transgenic mouse being created by injecting a gene for a rat growth hormone into a mouse embryo in 1982.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] In 1897 a bacterium that caused plant tumors, *Agrobacterium tumefaciens*, was discovered and in the early 1970s the tumor-inducing agent was found to be a DNA plasmid called the Ti plasmid.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] By removing the genes in the plasmid that caused the tumor and adding in novel genes, researchers were able to infect plants with *A. tumefaciens* and let the bacteria insert their chosen DNA into the genomes of the plants.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Not all plant cells are susceptible to infection by *A. tumefaciens*, so other methods were developed, including electroporation and micro-injection.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Particle bombardment was made possible with the invention of the Biolistic Particle Delivery System (gene gun) by John Sanford in the 1980s.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Competence refers to a temporary state of being able to take up exogenous DNA from the environment; it may be induced in a laboratory.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] It appears to be an ancient process inherited from a common prokaryotic ancestor that is a beneficial adaptation for promoting recombinational repair of DNA damage, especially damage acquired under stressful conditions.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Natural genetic transformation appears to be an adaptation for repair of DNA damage that also generates genetic diversity.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Transformation has been studied in medically important Gram-negative bacteria species such as *Helicobacter pylori*, *Legionella pneumophila*, *Neisseria meningitidis*, *Neisseria gonorrhoeae*, *Haemophilus influenzae* and *Vibrio cholerae*.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] It has also been studied in Gram-negative species found in soil such as *Pseudomonas stutzeri*, *Acinetobacter baylyi*, and Gram-negative plant pathogens such as *Ralstonia solanacearum* and *Xylella fastidiosa*.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Transformation among Gram-positive bacteria has been studied in medically important species such as *Streptococcus pneumoniae*, *Streptococcus mutans*, *Staphylococcus aureus* and *Streptococcus sanguinis* and in Gram-positive soil bacterium *Bacillus subtilis*.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] It has also been reported in at least 30 species of *Pseudomonadota* distributed in several different classes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] The best studied *Pseudomonadota* with respect to transformation are the medically important human pathogens *Neisseria gonorrhoeae*, *Haemophilus influenzae*, and *Helicobacter pylori*.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Naturally competent bacteria carry sets of genes that provide the protein machinery to bring DNA across the cell membrane(s).
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] The transport of the exogenous DNA into the cells may require proteins that are involved in the assembly of type IV pili and type II secretion system, as well as DNA translocase complex at the cytoplasmic membrane.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Due to the differences in structure of the cell envelope between Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria, there are some differences in the mechanisms of DNA uptake in these cells, however most of them share common features that involve related proteins.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] The DNA first binds to the surface of the competent cells on a DNA receptor, and passes through the cytoplasmic membrane via DNA translocase.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Only single-stranded DNA may pass through, the other strand being degraded by nucleases in the process.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] The translocated single-stranded DNA may then be integrated into the bacterial chromosomes by a RecA-dependent process.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] In Gram-negative cells, due to the presence of an extra membrane, the DNA requires the presence of a channel formed by secretins on the outer membrane.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Pilin may be required for competence, but its role is uncertain.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] The uptake of DNA is generally non-sequence specific, although in some species the presence of specific DNA uptake sequences may facilitate efficient DNA uptake.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Natural transformation is a bacterial adaptation for DNA transfer that depends on the expression of numerous bacterial genes whose products appear to be responsible for this process.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] The DNA integrated into the host chromosome is usually (but with rare exceptions) derived from another bacterium of the same species, and is thus homologous to the resident chromosome.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] In *B. subtilis* the length of the transferred DNA is greater than 1271 kb (more than 1 million bases).
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] The length transferred is likely double stranded DNA and is often more than a third of the total chromosome length of 4215 kb.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] It appears that about 7-9% of the recipient cells take up an entire chromosome.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] The capacity for natural transformation appears to occur in a number of prokaryotes, and thus far 67 prokaryotic species (in seven different phyla) are known to undergo this process.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Transformation in *Haemophilus influenzae* occurs most efficiently at the end of exponential growth as bacterial growth approaches stationary phase.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Transformation in *Streptococcus mutans*, as well as in many other streptococci, occurs at high cell density and is associated with biofilm formation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Competence in *B. subtilis* is induced toward the end of logarithmic growth, especially under conditions of amino acid limitation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Similarly, in *Micrococcus luteus* (a representative of the less well studied *Actinomycetota* phylum), competence develops during the mid-late exponential growth phase and is also triggered by amino acids starvation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] By releasing intact host and plasmid DNA, certain bacteriophages are thought to contribute to transformation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Competence is specifically induced by DNA damaging conditions.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] For instance, transformation is induced in *Streptococcus pneumoniae* by the DNA damaging agents mitomycin C (a DNA cross-linking agent) and fluoroquinolone (a topoisomerase inhibitor that causes double-strand breaks).
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] In *B. subtilis*, transformation is increased by UV light, a DNA damaging agent.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Of these, only six, all DNA damaging agents, caused strong induction.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] These DNA damaging agents were mitomycin C (which causes DNA inter-strand crosslinks), norfloxacin, ofloxacin and nalidixic acid (inhibitors of DNA gyrase that cause double-strand breaks), bicyclomycin (causes single- and double-strand breaks), and hydroxyurea (induces DNA base oxidation).
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] UV light also induced competence in *L. pneumophila*.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Charpentier et al. suggested that competence for transformation probably evolved as a DNA damage response.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Natural transformation in the extraordinarily radiation resistant bacterium *Deinococcus radiodurans* is associated with the repair of DNA damage under stressful conditions.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Logarithmically growing bacteria differ from stationary phase bacteria with respect to the number of genome copies present in the cell, and this has implications for the capability to carry out an important DNA repair process.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] During logarithmic growth, two or more copies of any particular region of the chromosome may be present in a bacterial cell, as cell division is not precisely matched with chromosome replication.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] The process of homologous recombinational repair (HRR) is a key DNA repair process that is especially effective for repairing double-strand damages, such as double-strand breaks.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] This process depends on a second homologous chromosome in addition to the damaged chromosome.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] During logarithmic growth, a DNA damage in one chromosome may be repaired by HRR using sequence information from the other homologous chromosome.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Once cells approach stationary phase, however, they typically have just one copy of the chromosome, and HRR requires input of homologous template from outside the cell by transformation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] The particular process responsible for repair was likely HRR.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Artificial competence can be induced in laboratory procedures that involve making the cell passively permeable to DNA by exposing it to conditions that do not normally occur in nature.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Typically the cells are incubated in a solution containing divalent cations (often calcium chloride) under cold conditions, before being exposed to a heat pulse (heat shock).
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Calcium chloride partially disrupts the cell membrane, which allows the recombinant DNA to enter the host cell.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Cells that are able to take up the DNA are called competent cells.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] It has been found that growth of Gram-negative bacteria in 20 mM Mg reduces the number of protein-to-lipopolysaccharide bonds by increasing the ratio of ionic to covalent bonds, which increases membrane fluidity, facilitating transformation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] The role of lipopolysaccharides here are verified from the observation that shorter O-side chains are more effectively transformed – perhaps because of improved DNA accessibility.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] The surface of bacteria such as *E. coli* is negatively charged due to phospholipids and lipopolysaccharides on its cell surface, and the DNA is also negatively charged.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] One function of the divalent cation therefore would be to shield the charges by coordinating the phosphate groups and other negative charges, thereby allowing a DNA molecule to adhere to the cell surface.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] DNA entry into *E. coli* cells is through channels known as zones of adhesion or Bayer's junction, with a typical cell carrying as many as 400 such zones.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Their role was established when cobalamine (which also uses these channels) was found to competitively inhibit DNA uptake.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Another type of channel implicated in DNA uptake consists of poly (HB):poly P:Ca.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] In this poly (HB) is envisioned to wrap around DNA (itself a polyphosphate), and is carried in a shield formed by Ca ions.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] It is suggested that exposing the cells to divalent cations in cold condition may also change or weaken the cell surface structure, making it more permeable to DNA.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] The heat-pulse is thought to create a thermal imbalance across the cell membrane, which forces the DNA to enter the cells through either cell pores or the damaged cell wall.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Electroporation is another method of promoting competence.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] In this method the cells are briefly shocked with an electric field of 10-20 kV/cm, which is thought to create holes in the cell membrane through which the plasmid DNA may enter.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] After the electric shock, the holes are rapidly closed by the cell's membrane-repair mechanisms.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Most species of yeast, including *Saccharomyces cerevisiae*, may be transformed by exogenous DNA in the environment.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Several methods have been developed to facilitate this transformation at high frequency in the lab.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] A number of methods are available to transfer DNA into plant cells.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] There are some methods to produce transgenic fungi most of them being analogous to those used for plants.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Introduction of DNA into animal cells is usually called transfection, and is discussed in the corresponding article.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] The discovery of artificially induced competence in bacteria allow bacteria such as *Escherichia coli* to be used as a convenient host for the manipulation of DNA as well as expressing proteins.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Typically plasmids are used for transformation in *E. coli*.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] In order to be stably maintained in the cell, a plasmid DNA molecule must contain an origin of replication, which allows it to be replicated in the cell independently of the replication of the cell's own chromosome.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] The efficiency with which a competent culture can take up exogenous DNA and express its genes is known as transformation efficiency and is measured in colony forming unit (cfu) per μg DNA used.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] A transformation efficiency of 1×108 cfu/μg for a small plasmid like pUC19 is roughly equivalent to 1 in 2000 molecules of the plasmid used being transformed.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] In calcium chloride transformation, the cells are prepared by chilling cells in the presence of Ca2+ (in CaCl 2 solution), making the cell become permeable to plasmid DNA.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] The cells are incubated on ice with the DNA, and then briefly heat-shocked (e.g., at 42 °C for 30–120 seconds).
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] This method works very well for circular plasmid DNA.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Non-commercial preparations should normally give 106 to 107 transformants per microgram of plasmid; a poor preparation will be about 104/μg or less, but a good preparation of competent cells can give up to ~108 colonies per microgram of plasmid.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Protocols, however, exist for making supercompetent cells that may yield a transformation efficiency of over 109.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] The chemical method, however, usually does not work well for linear DNA, such as fragments of chromosomal DNA, probably because the cell's native exonuclease enzymes rapidly degrade linear DNA.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] In contrast, cells that are naturally competent are usually transformed more efficiently with linear DNA than with plasmid DNA.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] The transformation efficiency using the CaCl 2 method decreases with plasmid size, and electroporation therefore may be a more effective method for the uptake of large plasmid DNA.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Cells used in electroporation should be prepared first by washing in cold double-distilled water to remove charged particles that may create sparks during the electroporation process.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Because transformation usually produces a mixture of relatively few transformed cells and an abundance of non-transformed cells, a method is necessary to select for the cells that have acquired the plasmid.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] The plasmid therefore requires a selectable marker such that those cells without the plasmid may be killed or have their growth arrested.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Antibiotic resistance is the most commonly used marker for prokaryotes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] The transforming plasmid contains a gene that confers resistance to an antibiotic that the bacteria are otherwise sensitive to.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] The mixture of treated cells is cultured on media that contain the antibiotic so that only transformed cells are able to grow.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Another method of selection is the use of certain auxotrophic markers that can compensate for an inability to metabolise certain amino acids, nucleotides, or sugars.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] This method requires the use of suitably mutated strains that are deficient in the synthesis or utility of a particular biomolecule, and the transformed cells are cultured in a medium that allows only cells containing the plasmid to grow.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] In a cloning experiment, a gene may be inserted into a plasmid used for transformation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] However, in such experiment, not all the plasmids may contain a successfully inserted gene.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Additional techniques may therefore be employed further to screen for transformed cells that contain plasmid with the insert.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Reporter genes can be used as markers, such as the *lacZ* gene which codes for β-galactosidase used in blue-white screening.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] This method of screening relies on the principle of α-complementation, where a fragment of the *lacZ* gene (*lacZα*) in the plasmid can complement another mutant *lacZ* gene (*lacZΔM15*) in the cell.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Both genes by themselves produce non-functional peptides, however, when expressed together, as when a plasmid containing *lacZ-α* is transformed into a *lacZΔM15* cells, they form a functional β-galactosidase.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] The presence of an active β-galactosidase may be detected when cells are grown in plates containing X-gal, forming characteristic blue colonies.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] However, the multiple cloning site, where a gene of interest may be ligated into the plasmid vector, is located within the *lacZα* gene.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Successful ligation therefore disrupts the *lacZα* gene, and no functional β-galactosidase can form, resulting in white colonies.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Cells containing successfully ligated insert can then be easily identified by its white coloration from the unsuccessful blue ones.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] Other commonly used reporter genes are green fluorescent protein (GFP), which produces cells that glow green under blue light, and the enzyme luciferase, which catalyzes a reaction with luciferin to emit light.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transformation-genetics] The recombinant DNA may also be detected using other methods such as nucleic acid hybridization with radioactive RNA probe, while cells that expressed the desired protein from the plasmid may also be detected using immunological methods.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] The discovery of transposable elements (TEs) by Barbara McClintock came many decades before during McClintock's early studies at the Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory (CSH) in New York.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Here, McClintock identified TEs in maize (*Zea mays*) during experimentation with plants which presented evidence of breaks in their chromosomes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] In the winter of 1944–1945, McClintock planted corn kernels that were self-pollinated, meaning that the silk (style) of the flower received pollen from its own anther.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] These kernels came from a long line of plants that had been self-pollinated, causing broken arms on the end of their ninth chromosomes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] As the plants began to grow, McClintock noted unusual color patterns on the leaves; for example, one leaf had two albino patches of almost identical size, located side by side on the leaf.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] McClintock hypothesized that during cell division certain cells lost genetic material, while others gained what they had lost.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] However, when comparing the chromosomes of the current generation of plants with the parent generation, she found certain parts of the chromosome had switched position.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] This refuted the popular genetic theory of the time that genes were fixed in their position on a chromosome.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] McClintock found that genes could not only move but they could also be turned on or off due to certain environmental conditions or during different stages of cell development.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] She also showed that these gene mutations could be reversed.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] In 1950, McClintock published her findings in *The Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences* (PNAS), in an article titled "The Origin and Behavior of Mutable Loci in Maize".
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] At the 1951 Cold Spring Harbor Symposium, where she first publicized her findings, her talk was met with silence.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Her work was largely dismissed and ignored until the late 1960s–1970s when after TEs were found in bacteria, their presence in eukaryotes was rediscovered.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] McClintock was awarded a Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1983 for her discovery of TEs, more than thirty years after her initial research.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Transposable elements represent one of several types of mobile genetic elements.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] TEs are assigned to one of two classes according to their mechanism of transposition, which can be described as either "*copy and paste"* (Class I TEs) or "*cut and paste"* (Class II TEs).
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Class I TEs are copied in two stages: first, they are transcribed from DNA to RNA, and the RNA produced is then reverse transcribed to DNA.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] RNA conversion back into DNA is then facilitated through an enzyme called reverse transcriptase which is often encoded by the TE itself.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] This newly copied DNA is then inserted back into the genome at a new position.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] The characteristics of retrotransposons are similar to retroviruses, such as HIV as HIV utilizes reverse transcriptase to make a double strand copy of its RNA genome which is then integrated into the host cells genome.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Despite the potential negative effects of retrotransposons self insertion into necessary DNA sequences, which can result in important genes becoming unusable, they are essential in keeping different species' ribosomal DNA (rDNA) intact over the generations, preventing infertility.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] The R2 retrotransposon of *Drosophila* creates double-stranded breaks by endonuclease activity during its process of replication within its target rDNA, allowing for homologous recombination between sister chromatids to repair the breaks.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] The resulting chromatids, each with different quantities of rDNA, are tagged and differentially segregated during asymmetric division of progenitors into daughter stem cells, which receive the chromatids with more rDNA, and germ cell precursors.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Long interspersed nuclear clusters encode for reverse transcriptase and are transcribed by RNA polymerase II.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Meanwhile SINEs do not encode for reverse transcriptase and are transcribed by RNA polymerase III.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] The cut-and-paste transposition mechanism of class II TEs does not involve an RNA intermediate.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] The transpositions are catalyzed by several transposase enzymes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Some transposases non-specifically bind to any target site in DNA, whereas others bind to specific target sequences.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] The transposase makes a staggered cut at the target site producing sticky ends, cuts out the DNA transposon and ligates it into the target site.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] A DNA polymerase fills in the resulting gaps from the sticky ends and DNA ligase closes the sugar-phosphate backbone.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] This results in target site duplication and the insertion sites of DNA transposons may be identified by short direct repeats (a staggered cut in the target DNA filled by DNA polymerase) followed by inverted repeats (which are important for the TE excision by transposase).
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Cut-and-paste TEs may be duplicated if their transposition takes place during S phase of the cell cycle, when a donor site has already been replicated but a target site has not yet been replicated.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Such duplications at the target site can result in gene duplication, which plays an important role in genomic evolution.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Not all DNA transposons transpose through the cut-and-paste mechanism.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] In some cases, a replicative transposition is observed in which a "complex transposon" replicates itself to a new target site (e.g. helitron).
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Class II TEs comprise less than 2% of the human genome, making the other transposons Class I.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Transposition can be classified as either "autonomous" or "non-autonomous" in both Class I and Class II TEs.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Autonomous TEs can move through the genome by themselves as they encode for their transpositional machinery allowing for their ability to move around the genome.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] This is contrasted by non-autonomous where they lack the ability to encode for their transposition machinery and require the presence of another TE machinery to move.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] This is often because dependent TEs lack transposase (for Class II) or reverse transcriptase (for Class I).
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Activator element (*Ac*) is an example of an autonomous TE, and dissociation elements (*Ds*) is an example of a non-autonomous TE.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Without *Ac,* *Ds* is not able to transpose.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Transposable elements can be all over a genome, and in the case of maize, TEs make up 50% of the genome.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] In yeast (which has 5 classes of retrotransposons, Ty1-Ty5), over 90% of the Ty1 through T4 elements are located within 750 bp upstream of genes transcribed by RNA polymerase III, particularly tRNA genes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] The Ty5 elements are all located at the telomeres or regions with telomeric chromatin.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] TEs are found in almost all life forms, and the scientific community is still exploring their evolution and their effect on genome evolution.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] It is unclear whether TEs originated in the last universal common ancestor, arose independently multiple times, or arose once and then spread to other kingdoms by horizontal gene transfer.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Because excessive TE activity can damage exons, many organisms have acquired mechanisms to inhibit their activity.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Bacteria may undergo high rates of gene deletion as part of a mechanism to remove TEs and viruses from their genomes, while eukaryotic organisms typically use RNA interference to inhibit TE activity.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Nevertheless, some TEs generate large families often associated with speciation events.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Evolution often deactivates DNA transposons, leaving them as introns (inactive gene sequences).
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] In vertebrate animal cells, nearly all 100,000+ DNA transposons per genome have genes that encode inactive transposase polypeptides.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] The first synthetic transposon designed for use in vertebrate (including human) cells, the Sleeping Beauty transposon system, is a Tc1/mariner-like transposon.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Its dead ("fossil") versions are spread widely in the salmonid genome and a functional version was engineered by comparing those versions.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Human Tc1-like transposons are divided into Hsmar1 and Hsmar2 subfamilies.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Although both types are inactive, one copy of Hsmar1 found in the SETMAR gene is under selection as it provides DNA-binding for the histone-modifying protein.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Many other human genes are similarly derived from transposons.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Hsmar2 has been reconstructed multiple times from the fossil sequences.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] TEs may affect gene regulatory networks and thus have evolutionary advantages.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Interspersed repeats are created by transposition; since they can inhibit gene conversion, they protect novel gene sequences from being overwritten by similar gene sequences and thereby facilitate the development of new genes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] TEs may also have been co-opted by the vertebrate immune system as a means of producing antibody diversity.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] The V(D)J recombination system operates by a mechanism similar to that of some TEs.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] TEs also serve to generate repeating sequences that can form dsRNA to act as a substrate for the action of ADAR in RNA editing.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] TEs can contain many types of genes, including those conferring antibiotic resistance and the ability to transpose to conjugative plasmids.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Some TEs also contain integrons, genetic elements that can capture and express genes from other sources.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] These contain integrase, which can integrate gene cassettes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] There are over 40 antibiotic resistance genes identified on cassettes, as well as virulence genes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Transposons do not always excise their elements precisely, sometimes removing the adjacent base pairs; this can lead to merged exons in a process called exon shuffling.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Shuffling two unrelated exons can create a novel gene product or, more likely, an intron.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Some non-autonomous DNA TEs found in plants can capture coding DNA from genes and shuffle them across the genome.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] This process can duplicate genes in the genome (a phenomenon called transduplication), and can contribute to generate novel genes by exon shuffling.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] There is a hypothesis that TEs might provide a ready source of DNA that could be co-opted by the cell to help regulate gene expression.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Research showed that many diverse modes of TEs co-evolution along with some transcription factors targeting TE-associated genomic elements and chromatin are evolving from TE sequences.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Most of the time, these particular modes do not follow the simple model of TEs and regulating host gene expression.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] One study estimated the rate of transposition of a particular retrotransposon, the Ty1 element in *Saccharomyces cerevisiae*.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Using several assumptions, the rate of successful transposition event per single Ty1 element came out to be about once every few months to once every few years.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Some TEs contain heat-shock like promoters and their rate of transposition increases if the cell is subjected to stress, thus increasing the mutation rate under these conditions, which might be beneficial to the cell.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] One hypothesis suggests that only approximately 100 LINE1 related sequences are active, despite their sequences making up 17% of the human genome.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] In human cells, silencing of LINE1 sequences is triggered by an RNA interference (RNAi) mechanism.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Surprisingly, the RNAi sequences are derived from the 5′ untranslated region (UTR) of the LINE1, a long terminal which repeats itself.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Supposedly, the 5′ LINE1 UTR that codes for the sense promoter for LINE1 transcription also encodes the antisense promoter for the miRNA that becomes the substrate for siRNA production.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Inhibition of the RNAi silencing mechanism in this region showed an increase in LINE1 transcription.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Cells defend against the proliferation of TEs in a number of ways.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] These include piRNAs and siRNAs, which silence TEs after they have been transcribed.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Certain mutated plants have been found to have defects in methylation-related enzymes (methyl transferase) which cause the transcription of TEs, thus affecting the phenotype.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] The second step of *de novo* repeat identification involves building a consensus of each family of sequences.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] A consensus sequence is a sequence that is created based on the repeats that comprise a TE family.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] A base pair in a consensus is the one that occurred most often in the sequences being compared to make the consensus.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Once a consensus sequence has been made for each family, it is then possible to move on to further analysis, such as TE classification and genome masking in order to quantify the overall TE content of the genome.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Transposable elements have been recognized as good candidates for stimulating gene adaptation, through their ability to regulate the expression levels of nearby genes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Combined with their "mobility", transposable elements can be relocated adjacent to their targeted genes, and control the expression levels of the gene, dependent upon the circumstances.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] The study conducted in 2008, "High Rate of Recent Transposable Element–Induced Adaptation in Drosophila melanogaster", used *D. melanogaster* that had recently migrated from Africa to other parts of the world, as a basis for studying adaptations caused by transposable elements.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Although most of the TEs were located on introns, the experiment showed a significant difference in gene expressions between the population in Africa and other parts of the world.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] The four TEs that caused the selective sweep were more prevalent in *D. melanogaster* from temperate climates, leading the researchers to conclude that the selective pressures of the climate prompted genetic adaptation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] From this experiment, it has been confirmed that adaptive TEs are prevalent in nature, by enabling organisms to adapt gene expression as a result of new selective pressures.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] However, not all effects of adaptive TEs are beneficial to the population.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] In the research conducted in 2009, "A Recent Adaptive Transposable Element Insertion Near Highly Conserved Developmental Loci in Drosophila melanogaster", a TE, inserted between Jheh 2 and Jheh 3, revealed a downgrade in the expression level of both of the genes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Downregulation of such genes has caused *Drosophila* to exhibit extended developmental time and reduced egg to adult viability.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Although this adaptation was observed in high frequency in all non-African populations, it was not fixed in any of them.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] This is not hard to believe, since it is logical for a population to favor higher egg to adult viability, therefore trying to purge the trait caused by this specific TE adaptation.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] At the same time, there have been several reports showing the advantageous adaptation caused by TEs.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] In the research done with silkworms, "An Adaptive Transposable Element insertion in the Regulatory Region of the EO Gene in the Domesticated Silkworm", a TE insertion was observed in the cis-regulatory region of the EO gene, which regulates molting hormone 20E, and enhanced expression was recorded.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] While populations without the TE insert are often unable to effectively regulate hormone 20E under starvation conditions, those with the insert had a more stable development, which resulted in higher developmental uniformity.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] These three experiments all demonstrated different ways in which TE insertions can be advantageous or disadvantageous, through means of regulating the expression level of adjacent genes.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] The field of adaptive TE research is still under development and more findings can be expected in the future.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Recent studies have confirmed that TEs can contribute to the generation of transcription factors.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] However, how this process of contribution can have an impact on the participation of genome control networks.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] TEs are more common in many regions of the DNA and it makes up 45% of total human DNA.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] Also, TEs contributed to 16% of transcription factor binding sites.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] A larger number of motifs are also found in non-TE-derived DNA, and the number is larger than TE-derived DNA.
[src:bacterial-genetics/transposable-element] All these factors correlate to the direct participation of TEs in many ways of gene control networks.
